@NODE Introduction
@TITLE "KidLock · Introduction"


    @{b}Introduction@{ub}


    KidLock is a simple commodity tool that locks keyboard and mouse
    inputs via a configurable key combination.

    KidLock is useful to protect the computer from kids, cats and drunk
    friends typing silliness on IRC.

    The key combination to lock inputs defaults to 'Control F1'. It
    can be modified with @{"tooltype" link ToolType} settings.

    Repeating of the key combination unlocks the keyboard and mouse.

    Keyboard and mouse inputs also can be locked by clicking the KidLock
    screenbar symbol. If mouse input is locked (see MOUSELOCK @{"tooltype" link ToolType}
    setting) then the hotkey can be used to unlock all inputs again.



@ENDNODE

@NODE Requirements
@TITLE "KidLock · Requirements"


    @{b}Requirements@{ub}


    o MorphOS 2.0 or better

    o A few KB free RAM

    o A few KB free hard disk space


@ENDNODE

@NODE Installation
@TITLE "KidLock · Installation"


    @{b}Installation@{ub}


    Copy KidLock to WBStartup. No installer required.



@ENDNODE

@NODE Startup
@TITLE "KidLock · Startup"


    @{b}Startup@{ub}


    KidLock can be launched from Ambient or from the CLI. If KidLock
    is installed in 'SYS:WBStartup' it will be launched automatically
    at system start.
 

    @{b}WBStartup@{ub}

    KidLock supports all default MUI and Commodity @{"tooltypes" link ToolType}.


    @{b}Ambient@{ub}

    KidLock supports all default MUI and Commodity @{"tooltypes" link ToolType}.


    @{b}CLI@{ub}

    It has no options. Just start it. If the KidLock icon is not found then
    default values for @{"tooltypes" link ToolType} will be used.


@ENDNODE

@NODE ToolType
@TITLE "KidLock · ToolType"


    @{b}Tooltypes@{ub}


    @{b}CX_PRIORITY@{ub}

    Adjusts the priority of the commodity. CX_PRIORITY range
    is -128 to 127. Defaults to 0.


    @{b}CX_LOCKKEY@{ub}

    CX_LOCKKEY defines the key combination that will lock and unlock the keyboard.
    Defaults to 'Control F1'.


    @{b}MOUSELOCK@{ub}

    MOUSELOCK excludes or includes mouse events from locking. Valid values are
    'ON' or 'OFF'. Setting this tooltype to 'ON' will lock the mouse. Defaults
    to 'OFF'.


    @{b}AUTOLOCK@{ub}

    The AUTOLOCK tooltype expects a numeric value which defines the timeout in seconds
    after which KidLock automatically locks keyboard and -if enabled- mouse inputs.
    Defaults to -1, automatic lock off.


    @{b}SCREENBARMODULE@{ub}

    If enabled a KidLock symbol is displayed in the screen titlebar which allows
    to activate input locking via mouse. Valid values are 'ON' or 'OFF'. Defaults
    to 'OFF'.

@ENDNODE


@NODE FAQ
@TITLE "KidLock · FAQ"


    @{b}Frequently Asked Question@{ub}


    o Why did you write KidLock?

      KidLock was written after some work was destroyed by my young children
      who were typing randomly at the keyboard.


    o How to remove KidLock?

      KidLock can be removed with Exchange or by launching it a second time.
      If launched from CLI, KidLock can be removed with CTRL+C.


    o Why 'Ctrl + Left Command + Right Command' isn't trapped?

      The keyboard reset combination can't be trapped in a system-friendly manner.
      The system handles that before the input device actually receives the input
      (KidLock uses system-friendly input.device API) and thus can not be trapped
      even with an input event handler at the highest priority.

      Patching Exec's ColdReboot() call isn't a solution either. This system call
      is not supposed to return. I tried to catch all incoming calls but it leads
      to a definitely messed up system.

      I don't know any system-friendly way to solve this. If anyone has a clue
      how to catch this, then be kind and drop an e-mail. :)



@ENDNODE


